SIMPLE: shoal
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shoal
<hw>Shoal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>scolu</ets>,
<ets>sceolu</ets>, a company, multitude, crowd, akin to OS.
<ets>skola</ets>; probably originally, a division, and akin to Icel.
<ets>skilja</ets> to part, divide. See <er>Skill</er>, and cf.
<er>School</er>. of fishes.]</ety> <def>A great multitude assembled; a
crowd; a throng; -- said especially of fish; <as>as, a <ex>shoal</ex> of
bass</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Great <xex>shoals</xex> of people.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Beneath, a <qex>shoal</qex> of silver fishes glides.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shoal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shoal
<hw>Shoal</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Shoaled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Shoaling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To assemble in a multitude; to
throng; <as>as, the fishes <ex>shoaled</ex> about the place</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Chapman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shoal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Shoal
<hw>Shoal</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Shallow</er>; or cf. G.
<ets>scholle</ets> a clod, glebe, OHG. <ets>scollo</ets>,
<ets>scolla</ets>, prob. akin to E. <ets>shoal</ets> a multitude.]</ety>
<def>Having little depth; shallow; <as>as, <ex>shoal</ex>
water</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shoal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Shoal
<hw>Shoal</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A place where the water
of a sea, lake, river, pond, etc., is shallow; a shallow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The depth of your pond should be six feet; and on the sides some
<qex>shoals</qex> for the fish to lay their span.</q>
<rj><qau>Mortimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wolsey, that once trod the ways of glory,⟦br⟧
And sounded all the depths and <qex>shoals</qex> of honor.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A sandbank or bar which makes the water
shoal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The god himself with ready trident stands,⟦br⟧
And opes the deep, and spreads the moving sands,⟦br⟧
Then heaves them off the <qex>shoals</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shoal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Shoal
<hw>Shoal</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become shallow; <as>as, the
color of the water shows where it <ex>shoals</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shoal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Shoal
<hw>Shoal</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cause to become more shallow;
to come to a more shallow part of; <as>as, a ship <ex>shoals</ex> her
water by advancing into that which is less deep</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Marryat.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shoaliness</ent>⟦br⟧
